Thank you. I think we talked about a bunch of the differences between this draft and the last one. I think the biggest question on the top of my mind is the council budget recommendations, the timeline for that and how that fits in with the preliminary budget meetings. I mean, as you noted,

81
00:32:49,732 --> 00:33:15,736
Councilor Beres, Vice President Beres, the previous draft that the Council or the subcommittee was looking at basically had us make recommendations after the meetings. This one has us make recommendations before. And so I think that's something that we should discuss. I know our time is limited. The other big differences, as noted, are things like the enterprise fund.

82
00:33:15,736 --> 00:33:43,293
the fixed costs versus new expenses, parts of the ordinance, capital improvements. Those are the biggest differences that I see in front of me today. I would also support Councilor Collins' statement that we should refer the part relevant to the school committee to school committee members to get their input on it as well.

83
00:33:45,385 --> 00:34:00,708
I'll just make two comments. I think for me one thing that would be very helpful and we can talk about this, this may not need to be in the ordinance itself. And it seems like actually you kind of already included it, which I do appreciate.

84
00:34:01,231 --> 00:34:30,863
In the general fund, when we see a departmental budget and we see the increase year over year, it would be helpful for me to know how much of that is fixed cost and how much of that is new program. And I think that would help us really explain to the public that when the budget goes up, it's not going up because we're not adding a new position. We're not adding a new service. We're not adding anything. It's very literally inflationary fixed cost increases. And I think that's a huge important thing to explain to residents that

85
00:34:30,863 --> 00:34:50,776
Yes, in nominal dollar terms, the dollar amount has increased, but we're not getting anything more for it. It's because salaries have increased, costs have increased, everything else. And I just think that's, that's really essential. It seems like you're kind of already there with the amount that's going towards new staff or programs. So I think just, you know, we could clarify that as a go forward, but

86
00:34:50,776 --> 00:35:19,598
It'd be really nice to see that in a really nice big graphical representation in every department sheet, like 90% of this increase is just paying for things that we're already doing today because costs have gone up. So that's just my one little throw in comment. And I would agree with that. Great. Thank you, Councilor Sang. Given where we are on the timeframe, I think I heard three motions. The first motion was from Councilor Collins.

87
00:35:19,700 --> 00:35:42,515
to refer the relevant section regarding the allocation to the school committee, to school committee members. Is that correct, Councilor Collins? Seconded by Councilor Sang. I think, and I'll wait for you. With some context though, obviously just, I mean, I don't know how you present it, but.

88
00:35:43,072 --> 00:36:04,604
probably be more helpful to send them this draft, and then the draft that came from the council for context. Sure. But the specific thing we're asking for a comment on is, do you have comments on the mayor saying that to put in ordinance that March 1st would be the date that the allocation would be provided to the school committee?

89
00:36:04,874 --> 00:36:33,410
I think, I mean, historically that the city has provided a number to the school committee. So this isn't gonna be any different than has been historical practice. No different than, you know, the administration has been able to work with the city council and provide for which departments will go first. This is memorializing that process to acknowledge that that's a critical element in order for this organization to be able to shift and provide revenue and other budget information as early as is being presented here.

90
00:36:34,220 --> 00:37:03,835
Got it. Understood. I think, is there an amendment to that motion, Councilor Collins? Has there been one? Would you like to make one? And that we will provide the drafts, both drafts of the budget ordinance as context. Yeah. All right. And the committee reports, which would contain what you just said. I think I kept your chair open.

91
00:37:18,027 --> 00:37:35,155
Great. A second motion that I didn't hear made, but I can't make, but I would like to happen is if counselors could submit to the clerk written comments on this, the draft from the administration by next Tuesday. So moved.

92
00:38:05,345 --> 00:38:20,127
Yes. Seconded by Councilor Collins. And the third motion would be to keep in committee and adjourn by Councilor Collins, seconded by Councilor Sang.

93
00:38:32,176 --> 00:39:00,492
And then to you guys, what do you think about the 12th or the 13th at 6 p.m. for a potential next meeting on this? Two weeks from today or two weeks from tomorrow.

94
00:39:06,635 --> 00:39:28,015
At this point, I think I could do the 13th, but I wouldn't take it straight to an hour. I could do the 13th. I'd rather not do the 12th. It's my birthday.

95
00:39:29,180 --> 00:39:58,407
Our finance director's birthday is apparently the 12th. So we probably should avoid that day. And I also was aiming towards the 13th, but I'd be constrained to an hour. I'm not sure if that could work for the subcommittee, but. Well, we can at least hopefully get pretty far. So we'll do that. All right. On the motion of councilor Collins to join and approve all the motions seconded by seconded by councilor saying all those in favor. All opposed. None.

96
